**Group 10 — Spiritual beings ****&**** cosmic language (reframed)**

**Domain: **spiritual-beings-reframed

These words appear in the text and readers encounter them. The entries do not explain what kind of supernatural being this is — they explain what the word actually meant in its original textual context, name the contamination that produced the supernatural reading, and apply GR-11 tier rules.

**GR-11 applies to all entries in this group: **Tier 1 rule for pre-exilic entries: physical/human reading is primary and the supernatural reading requires unavoidable textual warrant. Tier 2 rule for second-temple entries: the development is acknowledged honestly and named as such. Tier 3 rule for NT entries: first-century conceptual world is respected; systematic demonology must not be built from narrative accounts. All entries require a developmentalNote field.

| **Hebrew / Greek** | **Transliteration** | **Phase** | **Textual layer** | **Correct framing** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| מַלְאָךְ | mal'ak | P2 | pre-exilic | Messenger/agent — role not species. Same word for human and divine messengers. |
| נָחָשׁ | nachash | P2 | pre-exilic | Cunning creature of the field. Gen 3:1 names it explicitly as a creature YHWH made. Not Satan in disguise. |
| בְּנֵי הָאֱלֹהִים | bene ha-elohim | P2 | pre-exilic | Covenantal humans — Seth line (Gen 4:26) who marry outside the covenant community. Not angels. |
| נְפִילִים | nephilim | P2 | pre-exilic | Formidable people. Num 13:33 is the interpretive control — spies use the term to justify unbelief. Not angelic hybrids. |
| הַשָּׂטָן | ha-satan | P2 | pre-exilic | The adversary — role title with definite article. Prosecutorial function within YHWH's total sovereignty. Not a proper name in early texts. |
| שְׂרָפִים | seraphim | P2 | pre-exilic | Burning ones — cultic/literary imagery for divine holiness in Isaiah 6. A scene, not a species. Not an angelic rank. |
| כְּרוּבִים | keruvim | P2 | pre-exilic | Composite boundary-guardian figures — ancient Near Eastern threshold imagery. Always cultic/architectural. Not chubby Renaissance babies. |
| רוּחַ רָעָה | ruach ra'ah | P2 | pre-exilic | Disruptive spirit — 1 Sam 16:14 says explicitly it came from YHWH. YHWH's sovereignty includes disruptive agencies within his will. |
| שֵׁד / שֵׁדִים | shed/shedim | P2 | pre-exilic | Beings associated with illegitimate worship — Deut 32:17, Ps 106:37. Not "demons" in the modern sense. Foreign worship recipients named as non-YHWH powers. |
| רְפָאִים | refaim | P2 | pre-exilic | Two distinct usages: (1) ancient Canaanite peoples, (2) shades of the dead in Sheol. Both are human realities, not spirit species. |
| בְּלִיַּעַל | belial | P3 | second-temple | Worthlessness/ruin — an abstract quality personified in DSS. Not a named cosmic villain in Torah. |
| δαιμόνιον | daimonion | P3 | nt | First-century explanatory framework for medical conditions now clinically understood — epilepsy, psychosis, convulsions, schizophrenia. The Gospel claim is Jesus's authority, not demonic ontology. |
| διάβολος | diabolos | P3 | nt | Slanderer/accuser — LXX rendering of ha-satan. The adversarial function named in Greek. Milton's Satan must not be read back into this word. |
| ἄρχων / ἄρχοντες | archon/archontes | P3 | nt | Rulers — systemic forces of political and social oppression named as powers. Not a medieval spirit hierarchy. Their defeat in Christ is Paul's point. |
| στοιχεῖα τοῦ κόσμου | stoicheia tou kosmou | P3 | nt | Elemental powers governing the present age — Gal 4, Col 2. Translated as "basic principles" in many versions, losing the agency dimension entirely. |
| ἄγγελος | aggelos | P3 | nt | Messenger/agent — LXX rendering of mal'ak. Carries the same role-not-species meaning. Medieval angelology imposed a species taxonomy the Greek word does not contain. |

## **Appendix — Phase definitions**

| **Phase** | **Scope** | **Dependency** | **Count** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Phase 1 | 30 seed categories — the most load-bearing concepts across all groups | None — these are the starting point | 30 |
| Phase 2 | OT core categories that seed entries presuppose, depend on, or stand in contrast with. Expanding the Hebrew vocabulary coverage. | Phase 1 complete | 84 |
| Phase 3 | NT Greek and LXX vocabulary that must be explicitly routed through Hebrew antecedents. The highest contamination-risk entries. | Phase 2 complete (OT lexeme map) | 39 |

## **Appendix — textualLayer values**

| **Value** | **Definition** | **GR-11 tier** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| pre-exilic | Torah, early Prophets, pre-exilic Psalms — the foundational Hebrew conceptual world before Babylonian contact | Tier 1 — physical/human reading primary |
| exilic | Texts produced during or immediately responding to the Babylonian exile (586–538 BCE) | Tier 1 — physical/human primary; acknowledge exile context |
| post-exilic | Persian period texts (Ezra, Nehemiah, later Psalms, Chronicles) | Tier 1 with developmental awareness |
| second-temple | Intertestamental and late OT texts showing Zoroastrian/Mesopotamian developmental influence (Daniel late layers, some Psalms) | Tier 2 — developmental, not definitional |
| nt | New Testament — operates within first-century Second Temple Jewish conceptual world | Tier 3 — first-century frame, no systematic demonology |